      • getInstance

        public APersistentFormat<T> getInstance()
        Description copied from interface: IPersistentFormat
        Returns an instance of this format. Clients should always call this method before calling IPersistentFormat.read(Object, CharSequence) or IPersistentFormat.write(Object) and call these methods the returned value to avoid any unintended concurrent access.

        Example IPersistentFormat<?> format = getFormat(); format.getInstance().write(new Object()) Implementing classes may return this, if read and write are implemented in a static fashion (i.e., do not use any non-static fields).
        Specified by:
        getInstance in interface IPersistentFormat<T>
        Returns:
        An instance of this format.

      • read

        public ProblemList read(T object,
                        java.lang.CharSequence source)
        Description copied from interface: IPersistentFormat
        Parses the contents of the given source and transfers all information onto the given object. The object is intended to be completely overridden. A subclass may try to reset the information already stored inside the object, but is not obligated to do so. Thus, if possible an empty object should be passed here.
        Specified by:
        read in interface IPersistentFormat<T>
        Parameters:
        object - the object to write the information into.
        source - the source content.
        Returns:
        A list of problems that occurred during the parsing process.
        See Also:
        IPersistentFormat.supportsRead()
